<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">
   <teiHeader>
      <fileDesc>
         <titleStmt>
            <title>What sort of TEI do you want?</title>
         </titleStmt>
         <publicationStmt>
            <p>Information about publication or distribution</p>
         </publicationStmt>
         <sourceDesc>
            <p>Information about the source</p>
         </sourceDesc>
      </fileDesc>
   </teiHeader>
   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="slide">
            <head>What sort of TEI do you want?</head>
            <p>Specifically, what sort of standard should it be?</p>
            <list>
               <item>WKWBFY</item>
               <!-- we know what's best for you -->
               <item>DSTM</item>
               <!-- dont shoot the messenger -->
               <item>NECPUMP</item>
               <!-- nobody else can possbly understand my problem -->
            </list>
            <p rend="box">Or all three at once...</p>
         </div>
         <div type="slide">
            <head>Why do we even want one?</head>
            <list>
               <item>as an interface: helping locate and assess digital resources</item>
               <item>as a communication layer : helping integrate our own work with that of
                  others</item>
               <item>as an investment: resource creation is expensive; standardised resources can be
                  re-used</item>
            </list>
            <p rend="box">Because there are many FAQs</p>
         </div>

         <div type="slide">
            <head>What sort of TEI do we have?</head>
            <p>The current Guidelines contain ... <list>
                  <item>565 elements, 488 attributes, 189 classes, 62 schematron rules</item>
                  <item>content models </item>
                  <item>rules of praxis expressed directly in prose</item>
                  <item>and indirectly via examples</item>
               </list></p>
            <p>A (very) large number of existing use cases leading to many discipline-specific
               practices</p>
            <p rend="box">Confused? You may well be... </p>
         </div>
         <div>
            <head>Experts vs beginners...</head>
            <p><graphic height="50%" url="Graphics/boyhoodRaleigh.jpg"/></p>
            <list>
               <item>We got into this to make life easier for beginners, not more difficult!</item>
               <item>But also to make life easier for the specialist. </item>
            </list>
         </div>
         <div>
            <head>Researchers vs Technologists ...</head>
            <p><graphic url="Graphics/scientifique-ingenieur.jpg" height="50%"/></p>

            <list>
               <item>We rely on, and assume some understanding of, current mainstream
                  technologies</item>
               <item> But our conceptual model is firmly rooted in tradition, and a familiar view of
                     <soCalled>what text really is </soCalled></item>
            </list>

         </div>
         <div type="slide">
            <head>Personalisation is the key</head>
            <list>
               <item>TEI All is not the answer!</item>
               <item>TEI Simple is not the answer!</item>
            </list>
         <p> <figure><graphic height="50%" url="Graphics/oddflavours.png"/>
                  <head>ODD is the answer</head></figure>
         </p>
         </div>
         <div type="slide">
            <head>One Document Does it all</head>

            <p><figure>
                  <graphic url="Graphics/SGMLuser.png" height="75%"/>
                  <head> ICAME Journal, 1992</head>
               </figure></p>
            <cb/>
            <!--       <p>Le système TEI fournit un gabarit ou un kit lego pour la construction d'un système
                  d'encodage bien adapté aux besoins de l'utilisateur, qui reste en même temps
                  compréhensible par d'autres personnes ou systèmes, et dans lequel les modifications
                  éventuelles se déclarent clairement.</p>-->
            <list>
               <item>Which TEI elements do you use?</item>
               <item>What additional constraints do you need?</item>
               <item>What extensions will you make?</item>
               <item>And how does your project work anyway?</item>
            </list>
            <p>(And if you've identified a unicorn, ODD is what you should use to describe it)</p>
         </div>
         <div>
            <head>TEI Architecture</head>
            <p><graphic url="Graphics/class-system.png" height="80%"/></p>
         </div>

         <div>
            <head>Fictional example (1) </head>
            <p>
               <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples" rend="tiny">
                  <body>
                     <head>A TEI ODD for crowd sourced transcription </head>
                     <p>This document describes how we will mark up our crowd-sourced
                        transcriptions. <!-- several hundred pages missing here -->
                     </p>
                     <schemaSpec ident="transMin" start="TEI text div" docLang="fr">
                        <moduleRef key="tei"/>
                        <moduleRef key="header"
                           include="teiHeader fileDesc titleStmt 
                           publicationStmt sourceDesc"/>
                        <moduleRef key="textstructure" include="TEI text body div"/>
                        <elementRef key="ab"/>
                        <elementRef key="pb"/>
                        <elementRef key="unclear"/>
                        <elementRef key="hi"/>
                        <elementRef key="name"/>
                        <elementRef key="title"/>
                        <classRef key="att.global.rendition" except="rendition style"/>
                        <classSpec type="atts" ident="att.declaring" mode="delete"/>
                        <classSpec type="atts" ident="att.edition" mode="delete"/>
                        <classSpec type="atts" ident="att.editLike" mode="delete"/>
                     </schemaSpec>
                  </body>
               </egXML>
            </p>

         </div>
         <div>
            <head>Fictional example, contd </head>
            <p>On second thoughts, let's constrain the values for <code>hi/@rend</code></p>
            
               <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples" rend="tiny">
                  <!-- ... -->
                  <elementSpec ident="hi" mode="change">
                     <attList>
                        <attDef ident="rend" mode="replace">
                           <valList type="closed">
                              <valItem ident="underline"/>
                              <valItem ident="superscript"/>
                           </valList>
                        </attDef>
                     </attList>
                  </elementSpec>
                  <!-- ... -->
               </egXML>
      
            <cb/>
            <list>
               <item>the existing <gi>hi</gi> spec is changed</item>
               <item>the existing <att>rend</att> spec is replaced</item>
               <item>the list of available values for it is closed</item>
            </list>
         </div>
         <div>
            <head>Fictional example (contd) </head>
            <p rend="it">Oops, we need an element the TEI hasn't got! 
               </p>
            <egXML
                  xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples" rend="tiny">
                  <!-- ... -->
                  <elementSpec ident="botName" ns="http://monexcellentprojet.com">
                     <desc>botanical name </desc>
                     <classes>
                        <memberOf key="model.phrase"/>
                        <memberOf key="att.global"/>
                     </classes>
                     <content>
                        <macroRef key="macro.paraContent"/>
                     </content>
                  </elementSpec>
                  <!-- ... -->
               </egXML>
          
            <cb/>
            <list>
               <item>we supply a new specification for a new element, not in the TEI namespace </item>
               <item>this spec contains (at least) <list>
                     <item>a description</item>
                     <item>a list of the TEI classes to which the new element will belong</item>
                     <item>information about its content model</item>
                  </list>
               </item>
            </list>
         </div>
         <div>
            <head>Why your project needs an ODD</head>
            <list>
               <item>It communicates to others how you use the TEI</item>
               <item>It will keep you honest</item>
            </list>
            <p>ODDs can be <soCalled>chained</soCalled>: define one big one, and then select from it
               for particular levels or varieties of encoding praxis</p>
            <p>ODDs can be <soCalled>sourced</soCalled>: i.e. tied to a particular version of the
               Guidelines</p>
         </div>


